Gopnik (Russian: го́пник, IPA: [ˈɡopnʲɪk]) is a pejorative stereotype describing a particular subculture in Russia, former Soviet republics, and Russian-speakers in East Slavic countries to refer to young men or women of sometimes lower-class suburban areas (usually under 25 years of age) coming from families of poor education and income (sometimes), somewhat similar to American hoodlums, British chavs, Australian bogans, Scottish neds, Israeli Ars (for men) or Freḥa (for women), Dutch plebs, Icelandic slæpingjar, Brazilian favelados, Polish Dresy and Norwegian Harrys. The female form is gopnitsa (Russian: го́пница), and the collective noun is gopota (Russian: гопота́).
